#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:231
msgid "genspider"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:233
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy genspider [-t template] <name> <domain or URL>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:236
msgid ""
"Creates a new spider in the current folder or in the current project's "
"``spiders`` folder, if called from inside a project. The ``<name>`` "
"parameter is set as the spider's ``name``, while ``<domain or URL>`` is used "
"to generate the ``allowed_domains`` and ``start_urls`` spider's attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:240
msgid ""
"$ scrapy genspider -l\n"
"Available templates:\n"
"  basic\n"
"  crawl\n"
"  csvfeed\n"
"  xmlfeed\n"
"\n"
"$ scrapy genspider example example.com\n"
"Created spider 'example' using template 'basic'\n"
"\n"
"$ scrapy genspider -t crawl scrapyorg scrapy.org\n"
"Created spider 'scrapyorg' using template 'crawl'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:253
msgid ""
"This is just a convenient shortcut command for creating spiders based on pre-"
"defined templates, but certainly not the only way to create spiders. You can "
"just create the spider source code files yourself, instead of using this "
"command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:261
msgid "crawl"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:263
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy crawl <spider>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:264 ../../../topics/commands.rst:295
#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:326 ../../../topics/commands.rst:343
#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:470
msgid "Requires project: *yes*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:266
msgid "Start crawling using a spider."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:268 ../../../topics/commands.rst:376
#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:412 ../../../topics/commands.rst:436
#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:475
msgid "Supported options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:270
msgid "``-h, --help``: show a help message and exit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:272
msgid "``-a NAME=VALUE``: set a spider argument (may be repeated)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:274
msgid ""
"``--output FILE`` or ``-o FILE``: append scraped items to the end of FILE "
"(use - for stdout). To define the output format, set a colon at the end of "
"the output URI (i.e. ``-o FILE:FORMAT``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:276
msgid ""
"``--overwrite-output FILE`` or ``-O FILE``: dump scraped items into FILE, "
"overwriting any existing file. To define the output format, set a colon at "
"the end of the output URI (i.e. ``-O FILE:FORMAT``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:278 ../../../topics/commands.rst:301
#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:384
msgid "Usage examples::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:280
msgid ""
"$ scrapy crawl myspider\n"
"[ ... myspider starts crawling ... ]\n"
"\n"
"$ scrapy crawl -o myfile:csv myspider\n"
"[ ... myspider starts crawling and appends the result to the file myfile in "
"csv format ... ]\n"
"\n"
"$ scrapy crawl -O myfile:json myspider\n"
"[ ... myspider starts crawling and saves the result in myfile in json format "
"overwriting the original content... ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:292
msgid "check"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:294
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy check [-l] <spider>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:297
msgid "Run contract checks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:303
msgid ""
"$ scrapy check -l\n"
"first_spider\n"
"  * parse\n"
"  * parse_item\n"
"second_spider\n"
"  * parse\n"
"  * parse_item\n"
"\n"
"$ scrapy check\n"
"[FAILED] first_spider:parse_item\n"
">>> 'RetailPricex' field is missing\n"
"\n"
"[FAILED] first_spider:parse\n"
">>> Returned 92 requests, expected 0..4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:323
msgid "list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:325
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:328
msgid ""
"List all available spiders in the current project. The output is one spider "
"per line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:333
msgid ""
"$ scrapy list\n"
"spider1\n"
"spider2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:340
msgid "edit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:342
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy edit <spider>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:345
msgid ""
"Edit the given spider using the editor defined in the ``EDITOR`` environment "
"variable or (if unset) the :setting:`EDITOR` setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:348
msgid ""
"This command is provided only as a convenient shortcut for the most common "
"case, the developer is of course free to choose any tool or IDE to write and "
"debug spiders."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:354
msgid "$ scrapy edit spider1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:359
msgid "fetch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:361
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy fetch <url>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:364
msgid ""
"Downloads the given URL using the Scrapy downloader and writes the contents "
"to standard output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:367
msgid ""
"The interesting thing about this command is that it fetches the page the way "
"the spider would download it. For example, if the spider has a "
"``USER_AGENT`` attribute which overrides the User Agent, it will use that "
"one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:371
msgid ""
"So this command can be used to \"see\" how your spider would fetch a certain "
"page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:373
msgid ""
"If used outside a project, no particular per-spider behaviour would be "
"applied and it will just use the default Scrapy downloader settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:378 ../../../topics/commands.rst:414
#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:438 ../../../topics/commands.rst:477
msgid ""
"``--spider=SPIDER``: bypass spider autodetection and force use of specific "
"spider"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:380
msgid ""
"``--headers``: print the response's HTTP headers instead of the response's "
"body"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:382 ../../../topics/commands.rst:416
msgid ""
"``--no-redirect``: do not follow HTTP 3xx redirects (default is to follow "
"them)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:386
msgid ""
"$ scrapy fetch --nolog http://www.example.com/some/page.html\n"
"[ ... html content here ... ]\n"
"\n"
"$ scrapy fetch --nolog --headers http://www.example.com/\n"
"{'Accept-Ranges': ['bytes'],\n"
" 'Age': ['1263   '],\n"
" 'Connection': ['close     '],\n"
" 'Content-Length': ['596'],\n"
" 'Content-Type': ['text/html; charset=UTF-8'],\n"
" 'Date': ['Wed, 18 Aug 2010 23:59:46 GMT'],\n"
" 'Etag': ['\"573c1-254-48c9c87349680\"'],\n"
" 'Last-Modified': ['Fri, 30 Jul 2010 15:30:18 GMT'],\n"
" 'Server': ['Apache/2.2.3 (CentOS)']}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:403
msgid "view"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:405
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy view <url>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:408
msgid ""
"Opens the given URL in a browser, as your Scrapy spider would \"see\" it. "
"Sometimes spiders see pages differently from regular users, so this can be "
"used to check what the spider \"sees\" and confirm it's what you expect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:420
msgid ""
"$ scrapy view http://www.example.com/some/page.html\n"
"[ ... browser starts ... ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:426
msgid "shell"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:428
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy shell [url]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:431
msgid ""
"Starts the Scrapy shell for the given URL (if given) or empty if no URL is "
"given. Also supports UNIX-style local file paths, either relative with ``./"
"`` or ``../`` prefixes or absolute file paths. See :ref:`topics-shell` for "
"more info."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:440
msgid "``-c code``: evaluate the code in the shell, print the result and exit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:442
msgid ""
"``--no-redirect``: do not follow HTTP 3xx redirects (default is to follow "
"them); this only affects the URL you may pass as argument on the command "
"line; once you are inside the shell, ``fetch(url)`` will still follow HTTP "
"redirects by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:448
msgid ""
"$ scrapy shell http://www.example.com/some/page.html\n"
"[ ... scrapy shell starts ... ]\n"
"\n"
"$ scrapy shell --nolog http://www.example.com/ -c '(response.status, "
"response.url)'\n"
"(200, 'http://www.example.com/')\n"
"\n"
"# shell follows HTTP redirects by default\n"
"$ scrapy shell --nolog http://httpbin.org/redirect-to?"
"url=http%3A%2F%2Fexample.com%2F -c '(response.status, response.url)'\n"
"(200, 'http://example.com/')\n"
"\n"
"# you can disable this with --no-redirect\n"
"# (only for the URL passed as command line argument)\n"
"$ scrapy shell --no-redirect --nolog http://httpbin.org/redirect-to?"
"url=http%3A%2F%2Fexample.com%2F -c '(response.status, response.url)'\n"
"(302, 'http://httpbin.org/redirect-to?url=http%3A%2F%2Fexample.com%2F')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:467
msgid "parse"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:469
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy parse <url> [options]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:472
msgid ""
"Fetches the given URL and parses it with the spider that handles it, using "
"the method passed with the ``--callback`` option, or ``parse`` if not given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:479
msgid "``--a NAME=VALUE``: set spider argument (may be repeated)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:481
msgid ""
"``--callback`` or ``-c``: spider method to use as callback for parsing the "
"response"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:484
msgid ""
"``--meta`` or ``-m``: additional request meta that will be passed to the "
"callback request. This must be a valid json string. Example: --"
"meta='{\"foo\" : \"bar\"}'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:487
msgid ""
"``--cbkwargs``: additional keyword arguments that will be passed to the "
"callback. This must be a valid json string. Example: --cbkwargs='{\"foo\" : "
"\"bar\"}'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:490
msgid "``--pipelines``: process items through pipelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:492
msgid ""
"``--rules`` or ``-r``: use :class:`~scrapy.spiders.CrawlSpider` rules to "
"discover the callback (i.e. spider method) to use for parsing the response"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:496
msgid "``--noitems``: don't show scraped items"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:498
msgid "``--nolinks``: don't show extracted links"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:500
msgid "``--nocolour``: avoid using pygments to colorize the output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:502
msgid ""
"``--depth`` or ``-d``: depth level for which the requests should be followed "
"recursively (default: 1)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:505
msgid "``--verbose`` or ``-v``: display information for each depth level"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:507
msgid "``--output`` or ``-o``: dump scraped items to a file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:513
msgid ""
"$ scrapy parse http://www.example.com/ -c parse_item\n"
"[ ... scrapy log lines crawling example.com spider ... ]\n"
"\n"
">>> STATUS DEPTH LEVEL 1 <<<\n"
"# Scraped Items  "
"------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"[{'name': 'Example item',\n"
" 'category': 'Furniture',\n"
" 'length': '12 cm'}]\n"
"\n"
"# Requests  "
"-----------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"[]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:531
msgid "settings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:533
msgid "Syntax: ``scrapy settings [options]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:536
msgid "Get the value of a Scrapy setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/commands.rst:538
msgid ""
"If used inside a project it'll show the project setting value, otherwise "
"it'll show the default Scrapy value for that setting."
msgstr ""

